</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT ALMOND 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Six months ago, Valentine Mihov, then president of the Bulgarian soccer 
federation, called Egidius Braun, his German counterpart. 
</P>
<P>
 "Help," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Mihov, who resigned a week before World Cup '94, asked the Germans to help 
Bulgaria organize its team and send coaches, because it was in disarray. 
</P>
<P>
 But Braun never expected Bulgaria to knock off Germany, the defending 
champion, in the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
 "We did a lot of development," Braun said. "But it's good for soccer." ELLIOTT 
ALMOND 
</P>
