WORLD CUP USA '94 / THE FINALS; SPOTLIGHT; LOOK FOR A SALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIE CART 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Many of the really important parts of the World Cup are economic. 
</P>
<P>
 First, the organizers were hit with the failure of teams with huge fan bases 
to qualify -- England, France and Japan. Then, teams with relatively shallow 
pockets advanced. 
</P>
<P>
 Bulgaria, for one. 
</P>
<P>
 World Cup chairman Alan Rothenberg joked about Bulgaria's economic impact. 
</P>
<P>
 "Bulgaria cost us a lot of money," he said. "They kept France out in the first 
place (during qualifying), and then they knocked out Argentina and Mexico. Do 
you know how many T-shirts and novelties Bulgarians buy?" JULIE CART 
</P>
</TEXT>
