<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: NEWBURY PARK; POSTERS RIP BACKERS OF HOUSING PROJECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Newbury Park residents blanketed their neighborhood early Thursday with 
posters, saying "Dump the three development stooges," and other messages 
targeting the three Thousand Oaks City Council members who voted for the first 
phase of a massive housing project on the Dos Vientos Ranch. 
</P>
<P>
 The group, Residents to Preserve Newbury Park, placed dozens of colorful 
placards along neighborhood thoroughfares, protesting Mayor Alex Fiore's and 
council members Judy Lazar and Frank Schillo's support for the first 220 houses 
in the project. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to "Dump the three development stooges," the signs carried such 
messages as "Dos Vientos: Another gift to Newbury Park from Judy Lazar," and 
"Dos Vientos: Remember in November," a reference to upcoming city and county 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
 Michelle Koetke, who helped coordinate the protest campaign, said residents 
are mostly concerned about the increased traffic and pollution that the Dos 
Vientos project will bring to their neighborhood. The development could 
eventually include 2,350 houses in the foothills off Potrero Road. 
</P>
<P>
 "The community has really come together on this," Koetke said. "We're not 
going to give up. This is not over." 
</P>
<P>
 Schillo said the protest was politically motivated and not representative of 
most Newbury Park residents. The councilman is in a race for county supervisor 
with attorney Trudi Loh, who is running as an environmentalist opposing the Dos 
Vientos project. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think this is a small group of people who are trying to gain more ground 
politically," said Schillo. He helped negotiate a 1987 agreement with the two 
Dos Vientos developers that guarantees them the right to build 2,350 homes in 
exchange for $12.6 million in fees for the city. 
</P>
<P>
 If the city were to violate that agreement, Schillo said, it would open itself 
up to lawsuits. To address some residents' concerns, however, he has suggested 
forming two citizens committees to monitor the development and to come up with 
recommendations on how to spend the developer fees generated by the project. 
CARLOS V. LOZANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
